{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653689"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:47:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:47:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18590"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18590"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.23,0.73,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11322"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79769"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11322"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18590"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65074"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10384"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26236"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26243"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79769"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe visual system processes information through a hierarchical series of cortical regions, beginning with the primary visual cortex and progressing to specialised association areas.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the visual association area?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Generates visual hallucinations","Controls eye movements","Receives direct input from retinal ganglion cells","Processes complex visual features","Detects simple light patterns"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprocesses complex visual features\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of the visual association area. This region integrates basic visual information from the primary visual cortex to enable recognition of objects, faces, colours, and motion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerates visual hallucinations\u003C/strong\u003E - While damage to visual areas can cause hallucinations, this is not a normal function of the visual association area\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControls eye movements\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily managed by the frontal eye fields and superior colliculus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReceives direct input from retinal ganglion cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Retinal ganglion cells project to the lateral geniculate nucleus, which then projects to the primary visual cortex, not the association areas\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetects simple light patterns\u003C/strong\u003E - This basic visual processing occurs in the primary visual cortex\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDamage to the visual association area can result in various forms of visual agnosia, where patients can see objects but cannot recognise or identify them, despite intact basic vision.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The visual association area processes complex visual information including colour, motion, and form recognition.","The primary visual cortex receives direct input from the lateral geniculate nucleus but must send information to association areas for higher processing.","Visual association areas integrate information from both hemispheres via the corpus callosum to form complete visual perceptions."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18590"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65074"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T16:53:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T16:58:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11322"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79769"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17